               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18430821-2561-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2561-18430821 t18430821-2561-offence-1 t18430821-2561-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2561. <persName id="def1-2561-18430821" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2561-18430821" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2561-18430821" type="surname" value="LEADBURY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2561-18430821" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">HENRY LEADBURY</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18430821-2561-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430821-2561-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430821-2561-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18430821-cd-301" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430821-2561-offence-1 t18430821-cd-301"></join>21st of July</rs>, 1 pair of trowsers, value 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 1 waistcoat, 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; and 1 handker<lb></lb>chief, 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18430821-name-1720" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1720" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1720" type="surname" value="MAYBANK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1720" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430821-2561-offence-1 t18430821-name-1720"></join>Joseph Maybank</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1721" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1721" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1721" type="surname" value="MAYBANK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1721" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH MAYBANK</persName>
                  </hi>. I do not know the prisoner—I never sent him for my trowsers, waistcoat, and handkerchief.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1722" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1722" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1722" type="surname" value="MAYBANK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1722" type="given" value="SUSANNAH"></interp>SUSANNAH MAYBANK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prosecutor's wife—we live in Creek-street, Deptford. On the 21st of July, the prisoner came and told me my husband had met with a misfortune, and had sent him for some clothes—I believed his story, and gave him a waistcoat, a pair of trowsers, and a hand<lb></lb>kerchief I am sure he is the man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You never saw the man before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—it was on Friday he came to me, and on the Tuesday afterwards I saw him in the churchyard, and gave him into custody—he said some vitriol had been dropped on my husband's clothes—I was rather alarmed—he said my husband was not hurt—I have said that I thought the prisoner was the man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are you sure he is the man? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I think he is—he came to me on Friday the 21st of July, at twenty minutes or a quarter before twelve o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1723" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1723" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1723" type="surname" value="BRYDGES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1723" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS BRYDGES</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at No. 9, Creek-street, Deptford, four doors from Mrs. Maybank. On the 21st of July, a man who I think was the pri<lb></lb>soner, came to my place, from a quarter past eleven to half-past—he asked if there was a man named Chuck, who drove a cart—I said there was an old man—he said he did not want the old man—he wanted the young one.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you hear that Mrs. Maybank had been imposed on by somebody? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not till I came home at night.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1724" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1724" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1724" type="surname" value="AYRES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1724" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM AYRES</persName>
                  </hi>. On Friday, the 21st of July, I was at my master's yard in Cooper's-lane—two or three minutes' walk from Creek-street—about twelve o'clock the prisoner came and asked if a man worked there named Chuck—I said, "No"—he said he did not want the old man, he wanted the young man—he asked me if he was at home—I told him no—he asked his name and where he lived—I said his name was Maybank, and he lived the third house down Creek-street—I am sure the prisoner is the man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> That was the first time you saw him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yet—I did not see him again until he was in custody—I heard, about two hours after I saw the man, that a trick had been played.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1725" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1725" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1725" type="surname" value="ROBERTS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1725" type="given" value="MARIA"></interp>MARIA ROBERTS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at No. 47, James-street, Camberwell New-road. My husband is a salesman—the prisoner and his wife lodge in my house—on Friday, the 21st of July, he was at home till twelve o'clock—I had known him for about a month previous—he was taken into custody on the Tuesday follow<lb></lb>ing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How do you come to recollect Friday the 21st? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have been in the habit of giving his wife washing, and I did so that day—some of the things wanted mending, and I wanted her to sit in my room and do them—she said she would rather not, for her old man was up stairs, and she wished him to go out, as she did not like to have washing about in the room when he was at home—I know this was on Friday as that is my washing day—she has always washed on Friday ever since she has been there—Mary</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184308210228"></xptr>
               <p>Berry was in the house at the time, and I believe she saw the prisoner—she is not here—I am not aware that any one else was present—the prisoner was up stairs in his room—I saw him when he came down to go out—he had light kerseymere trowsers and waistcoat on, and the jacket he has on now—I have not known Hempstead previously, but I have seen him here to day—he is a journeyman baker, and lives in Southampton-street, Camberwell—I did not come here with him—I came with the prisoner's wife—the pri<lb></lb>soner came back between five and six, or six o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had the beer man come round? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He was coming up the street—he comes at twelve o'clock, and the prisoner was then going out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1726" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1726" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1726" type="surname" value="HEMPSTEAD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1726" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM HEMPSTEAD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a journeyman baker, in the employ of Mr. Horsley, of Southampton-street, Camberwell. The prisoner is a journeyman baker also—I remember his being taken into custody on a Tuesday—on the Friday previous to that, I saw him in Camberwell New-road, as I was carry<lb></lb>ing my twelve o'clock bakings home—I had my board on my head—he re<lb></lb>mained with me till a quarter past one o'clock—he went along with me by my master's shop.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How was he dressed? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He had a pair of light coloured trowsers—I think they were pepper and salt colour.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1727" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1727" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1727" type="surname" value="AYRES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1727" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM AYRES</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined. Q.</hi> What coloured trowsers had the man on that you saw? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> A pair of light kerseymere trowsers—I am sure it was about twelve o'clock—my place is four or five miles from Mrs. Roberts.</p>
               <p>
